{
  "answer": "**In Manusmṛti chapter 5, the text mentions impurity (*aśauca*) arising from childbirth and death in the context of prohibited foods.**\n\nOne passage notes that food should be avoided \"from a house under impurity from childbirth\" (referring to the period of ritual pollution following a birth).[^1] Another specifies avoiding \"food offered to a corpse before the ten days of impurity are over,\" indicating a standard ten-day period of impurity after death.[^2]\n\nThese references appear amid a longer list of impure or forbidden foods (Manusmṛti 4.212–217, placed at the start of the chapter 5 translation). The text does not provide further details on the exact duration for birth impurity here (though a later parallel in 5.58, in chapter 6, equates it to the ten-day death impurity for sapindas/kinsmen). No more specific rules on varying periods by caste or kin relation appear in chapter 5 itself.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-7851cc).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-15103f).\n[^3]: Manusmṛti, [chapter](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/06/translation/).",
